Kristyn Beam, Alex Rashedi, and Luis Castelo Branco

12/13/2020

Examining the Effects of Nonpharmaceutical Interventions on the Incidence of COVID-19 and Other Infectious Diseases in Australia

Overview and motivation

COVID-19 has rocked the globe in the year 2020. With it’s emergence in Wuhan, China in late 2019, high contagiousness, and lack of available medical treatments and interventions, nonpharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) have been the main defense against its spread. Given this fact, investigation into how NPIs have not only affected the spread of COVID-19, but also other infectious diseases transmitted by physical contact or respiratory droplets, is warranted.

Influenza is another infectious disease that is tracked annually and globally, and it has a typical course of increased incidence in the winter (colder) months, virtually disappearing in the summer (warmer) months. COVID-19 emerged in December of 2019 but became particularly prevalent in March of 2020. In the United States (US), “influenza season” is typically November to March, where incidence decreases until the following Fall. Given the non-overlapping seasons for high COVID-19 and influenza incidence in the US, in particular, we decided to conduct the investigation using data from a country in the Southern Hemisphere, instead, where the periods of high incidence would track more closely. Australia was selected for study, as it has a national data collection system for infectious disease incidence as well as national- and regional-level policy institution for COVID-19 management, lending itself well to analyses of the effects of these policy changes on the incidences of COVID-19 and other infectious diseases of interest.

Related work

An article published recently in Nature examined how specific policy changes (i.e., NPIs) have affected the incidence of COVID-19, globally.

“The most effective NPIs include curfews, lockdowns and closing and restricting places where people gather in smaller or large numbers for an extended period of time. This includes small gathering cancellations (closures of shops, restaurants, gatherings of 50 persons or fewer, mandatory home working and so on) and closure of educational institutions.”

We hypothesize that these NPIs have considerable effects on COVID-19 incidence but may also impact the incidences of other infectious diseases.

Initial questions

Our questions for this project were whether NPIs instituted to limit the spread of COVID-19 also had an effect on other infectious diseases, with a focus on influenza. There are eight states/territories in Australia: New South Wales, Australian Capital Territory, Queensland, Victoria, Tasmania, Southern Australia, Western Australia, and the Northern Territory. We examined several NPIs discussed in the article cited above, including, but not limited to: Lockdown, Public Awareness, Health Monitoring, Health Resources, Social Distancing, Restriction of Mass Gatherings, and Closure of Schools.

Our initial intention was to investigate how the incidence of COVID-19 and influenza changed over time as new policy restrictions were introduced in each region of Australia. As we further explored our data sources, we found that there were several infectious diseases tracked by Australia, allowing us to look at changes in multiple gastrointestinal (GI), respiratory, and sexually transmitted infections (STIs) of interest using both graphical representations and statistical analyses.

Our plan for statistical analysis was to compare the mean incidence rates of both COVID-19 and influenza over the months prior to the specific NPI implemenatation to the mean incidence rates for each over the months after NPI implementation.

Data sources

We obtained our data from several sources:

  1. Australian infectious disease data, located here.

  2. Australian COVID-19 data, located here.

  3. NPI data, located here. This project’s goal is to “…compile a database on government responses to the coronavirus. [The] main focus is to collect as much information as we can about the various fine-grained actions governments are taking to address the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic. To date, this dataset provides the most comprehensive and granular documentation of such government policies in the world, capturing data for 18 broad policy categories alongside many other dimensions, including the initiator, target and timing of a policy.”

We downloaded several of the pre-fabricated .csv files from the listed websites. Given that the CoronaNet Research Project is updated frequently, we used webscraping to download this data in order to utilize the most up-to-date information each time our analysis was updated and/or performed.

We performed numerous data management tasks with the infectious disease data to prepare both count and rate information for analyses, including recoding, filtering, mutating, merging, and transforming. We engaged in similar tasks for the NPI data. Finally, we ensured that all variables across all datasets had the appropriate variable names and type designations for use in our Shiny app.

Exploratory data analyses

We first generated exploratory line plots of our infectious disease data to look at counts and rates of COVID-19 and other infectious diseases across time based on state/territory to explore baseline rates for various diseases.

We created a dataframe aus_total_high which restricted the final dataset to include only those diseases with a rate greater than 0.2 (new confirmed cases per million). This removed extremely rare diseases from inclusion in our analysis, and the diseases that were removed with this method were mostly mosquito-borne.

Lastly, we limited the NPI dataset to only include observations for the first date that each policy type was introduced within each state/territory. Then, we produced a test graph to explore how a vertical line displaying the date for the start of each of these policies visually mapped onto infectious disease incidence within each region.

  select("Disease":"Aust_n") %>% 
  rename("ACT" = "ACT_n", 
         "NSW" = "NSW_n", 
         "NT" = "NT_n", 
         "Qld" = "Qld_n", 
         "SA" = "SA_n", 
         "Tas" = "Tas_n", 
         "Vic" = "Vic_n", 
         "WA" = "WA_n", 
         "Australia" = "Aust_n") %>% 
  arrange("Date") %>% 
  gather(State, 
         Cases, 
         c("ACT":"Australia"))

# Create rate data frame and reshape to long format
aus_data_rates <- aus_data %>% 
  select("Disease"|"Date"|"ACT_rate":"Aust_rate") %>% 
  rename("ACT" = "ACT_rate", 
         "NSW"="NSW_rate", 
         "NT"="NT_rate", 
         "Qld"="Qld_rate", 
         "SA"="SA_rate", 
         "Tas"= "Tas_rate", 
         "Vic"="Vic_rate", 
         "WA"="WA_rate", 
         "Australia"="Aust_rate") %>% 
  arrange("Date") %>% 
  gather(State, 
         Rates, 
         c("ACT":"Australia")) 

# Join cases and rates data frames
aus_total <- left_join(aus_data_cases, 
                       aus_data_rates)

# Read in Australian policy data by pulling most up-to-date version from Github
pol_dat_aus = read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/saudiwin/corona_tscs/master/data/CoronaNet/data_country/coronanet_release/coronanet_release_Australia.csv")

pol_dat_aus <- pol_dat_aus %>%
  # Group pol_dat_aus by province and policy type
  group_by(province, 
           type) %>%
  # Arrange by date policy goes into effect
  arrange(date_start) %>%
  # Keep only first observation within each province-policy type group
  slice(1) %>%
  # Ungroup
  ungroup() %>%
  # Filter to keep only policies that target Australia
  filter(target_country == "Australia")

# Transform variable types
pol_dat_aus$type <- as.factor(pol_dat_aus$type)
pol_dat_aus$type_sub_cat <- as.factor(pol_dat_aus$type_sub_cat)
pol_dat_aus$target_who_what <- as.factor(pol_dat_aus$target_who_what)

# Create a variable: drop in influenza cases from year 1 (Nov/18 to Oct/19) to year 2 (Nov19 to Oct/20)
aus_total_influenza_year1 <- aus_total_influenza %>% 
  filter(Date <= "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year1 = sum(Cases))

aus_total_influenza_year2 <- aus_total_influenza %>% 
  filter(Date > "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year2 = sum(Cases))

aus_total_influenza_diff <- left_join(aus_total_influenza_year1,
                                      aus_total_influenza_year2) %>%
  mutate(drop = (year1 - year2) / year1)
# Perform web scraping for a dataset that containd the population and population density for the provinces
url <- "https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/which-australian-states-territories-have-the-highest-density-of-population.html"
h <- read_html(url)
density <- h %>% 
  html_nodes("table") %>%
  .[1]
density <- density %>% 
  html_table %>% 
  .[[1]] 

density <- density %>%
  rename("State" = "State / Territory") %>%
  rename("density" = "Density (persons per km2)") %>% 
  mutate(State = recode(State, 
                        "Australian Capital Territory" = "ACT", 
                        "New South Wales" = "NSW", 
                        "Northern Territory" = "NT", 
                        "Queensland" = "Qld", 
                        "South Australia" = "SA", 
                        "Tasmania" = "Tas", 
                        "Victoria" = "Vic", 
                        "Western Australia" = "WA"))

density$Population <- as.numeric(gsub(",", 
                                      "", 
                                      density$Population))

# Join the datasets
aus_total_influenza_diff <- left_join(aus_total_influenza_diff, 
                                      density)

T-tests

# Build statistical tests to see if the mean cases of a disease in the first year (without COVID-19) was different from the mean cases in the second year (with COVID-19)

# Example with Influenza
aus_total_influenza_year1 <- aus_total_high %>% 
  filter(Disease == "Influenza (laboratory confirmed)") %>%
  filter(Date <= "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year1 = mean(Cases))

aus_total_influenza_year2 <- aus_total_high %>%
  filter(Disease == "Influenza (laboratory confirmed)") %>%
  filter(Date > "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year2 = mean(Cases))

aus_total_influenza_test <- left_join(aus_total_influenza_year1, 
                                      aus_total_influenza_year2) %>%
  filter(State != "Australia")

t.test(aus_total_influenza_test$year1, 
       aus_total_influenza_test$year2, 
       paired = TRUE, 
       alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  aus_total_influenza_test$year1 and aus_total_influenza_test$year2
## t = 2.6818, df = 7, p-value = 0.03146
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   350.772 5580.678
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##                2965.725

  summarize(year2 = mean(Cases))

aus_total_Rota_test <- left_join(aus_total_Rota_year1, 
                                 aus_total_Rota_year2) %>%
  filter(State != "Australia")

t.test(aus_total_Rota_test$year1, 
       aus_total_Rota_test$year2, 
       paired = TRUE, 
       alternative = "two.sided")
## 
##  Paired t-test
## 
## data:  aus_total_Rota_test$year1 and aus_total_Rota_test$year2
## t = 1.2007, df = 6, p-value = 0.2751
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -16.74111  49.00302
## sample estimates:
## mean of the differences 
##                16.13095
# Example with Pertussis
aus_total_Pertussis_year1 <- aus_total_high %>% 
  filter(Disease == "Pertussis") %>%
  filter(Date <= "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year1 = mean(Cases))

aus_total_Pertussis_year2 <- aus_total_high %>% 
  filter(Disease == "Pertussis") %>%
  filter(Date > "2019-10-31") %>%
  group_by(State) %>%
  summarize(year2 = mean(Cases))

aus_total_Pertussis_test <- left_join(aus_total_Pertussis_year1, 
                                      aus_total_Pertussis_year2) %>%
  filter(State != "Australia")

       aus_total_Pertussis_test$year2,

       alternative = "two.sided")

Final conclusions

We found that several non-pharmaceutical interventions also had an effect on other communicable diseases including influenza, chlamydia, and pertussis. It did not seem that GI illnesses decreased in incidence as much according to NPI implementation. These conclusions were drawn visually from our shiny app.

We performed t-tests to examine the difference in mean cases of diseases in year 1 (2019) and year 2 (2020).

Influenza: p = 0.03, statistically significant difference between 2019 and 2020. Gonococcal infection: p = 0.25; no difference in infections between 2019 and 2020 Hepatitis C: p = 0.06, no significant difference in infections between 2019 and 2020 Rotavirus: p = 0.28, no significant difference in infections between 2019 and 2020 Pertussis: p = 0.12, no significant difference in infections between 2019 and 2020

Ultimately, we see that although visually there appears to be a difference between infection rates for a variety of disorders with the implementation of NPIs, it does not appear that these differences are statistically significant with the exception of influenza. As stated prior, in Australia, COVID and influenza season have coexisted and they have similar precautions to limit spread of the diseases. The other diseases we investigated include GI illnesses and bloodborne illnesses which perhaps do not respond to NPI interventions as readily.
